item.title: Detected RS2 Client Version: #471
item.dc:creator: @sh_ft sh!ft
item.description:
@sh_ft wrote:

A system needs to meet a number of goals:

  1. Is the system stable?
  2. Can the system function without user interaction?
  3. Does it automate a player and work towards something?
  4. Has the system implemented bypasses for all possible means of detectability found within the client?

item.title: Detected RS2 Client Version: #471
item.dc:creator: @semaphore semaphore
item.description:
@semaphore wrote:

[quote=“BAsh(CntLgn), post:9, topic:145473”]OMG it took a total of 3sec. Mine runs about 20sec and no you are not having it.

The real question is whether it is faster than a human doing the same job. If it takes somebody experienced 2days to do it who gives a toss if the program can do it in 2hrs? Build something that actually works rather than optimising the hell out of it.[/quote]

Precisely.

What’s the point of an updater that updates in 34ms but sits in front of a useless system? Everyone seems to enjoy boasting about the speed of their updater logic, yet I have not seen a single post about significant botting topics: world traveling (given a world location the bot will move to that location no matter where it is), script pausing for random event handling(effective practices for pausing a bot reliably for random event handling), resource management (getting your bots to run at ~3% cpu without risking blatant detection).

Where are those discussions held? They sure as hell are not talked about in any part of this forum, secret or otherwise. Instead, the only topics of discussion involve a few leeches and paramecium showing how fast their standalone updater has detected new variables. whoopity-doo.

Read full topic
